of the property)."]}]},{"name":"ROHAN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Kieran, Oonagh, Padraig, Siobhan.","Irish (Kerry and Cork): from <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b> or <b>Ó Robhacháin</b>, see   Rowan  .","Breton and English: habitational name from Rohan in Morbihan, Brittany (France)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rowan","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó Ruadháin</b> or <b>Ó Ruaidhín</b>, both meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ruadhán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’. See also   Rooney  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b>, ‘son of <i>Ruadhachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ (also used as a placename and Anglicized as <i>Roughan</i>). Compare also   Rogan   (<b>Ó Ruadhagáin</b>), of which may be a variant, both it and <b>Ó Ruadhacháin</b> being found in Ulster and Connacht.","Irish: from <b>Ó Robhacháin</b>, the name of a scattered ecclesiastical family, found in Clare in the 16th and 17th centuries. The personal name was earlier <i>Reabhachán</i> ‘skillful, artful’."]}]},{"name":"Constance","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval form of the Late Latin name <i>Constantia</i>, which is either a feminine derivative of <i>Constans</i> (  see  Constant  ) or an abstract noun meaning ‘constancy’. This was a popular name among the Normans, and was borne by, amongst others, the formidable Constance of Sicily (  1158–98 ), wife of the Emperor  Henry VI ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Constance de ROHAN was born about 1166, in Guilliers, Morbihan, Brittany, France, her father, Alain III de Rohan, was 32 and her mother, Constance dE PENTHIèVRE, was 31. She married Eudon De Pontchateau. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"ABT 1166–":"umbes 1166–Surnud","1158–1203":"1158–1203","1164–1208":"1164–1208